        <Parent_String>bowl lyres [300042119], lyres [300042114], chordophones [300041641], sound devices by acoustical characteristics [300041621], sound devices (equipment) [300387677], Sound Devices (hierarchy name) [300041619], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bowl lyres of ancient Greece, having a tortoise-shell resonator (or its imitation in wood), skin belly, two carved arms projecting from the bowl and connected at the top by a crossbar, and a variable number of gut strings of equal length.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000026541/Marcuse, Musical Instruments Dictionary (1975)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Liras de bol de la Antigua Grecia que tienen un resonador de caparazón de tortuga (o una imitación en madera), vientre de piel, dos brazos tallados proyectándose desde el bol y conectados en el extremo superior por un travesaño, y con un número variable de cuerdas de tripa de igual longitud.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Schaallieren, klankbodem van het schild van een schildpad, ook een houten imitatie hiervan, onderblad van huid, 2 armen met houtsnijwerk die uit de schaal steken en bovenaan met elkaar verbonden door een dwarsbalk, wisselend aantal darmsnaren van gelijke lengte; Griekenland, 2de eeuw v.Chr.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052452/Encyclopedie van muziekinstrumenten (1977)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指古希臘的碗狀里拉琴，具有龜殼製或木製龜殼狀共鳴器、皮製琴肚以及兩隻具雕刻的琴臂，琴臂自共鳴器延伸出，再於琴頂由橫木連接，並有數條等長的羊腸弦。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Schalenleier des antiken Griechenland mit einem Resonanzkörper aus Schildpatt oder später Schildpattnachbildungen aus Holz, einer Membrandecke und zwei geschnitzten Jocharmen, die aus dem Korpus herausragen und an der Spitze mit einem Querjoch verbunden sind, sowie einer variablen Anzahl von Darmsaiten gleicher Länge.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
